        "body": "This improves tracking of in-flight packets.  Most importantly, it\r\nremoves the distinction we were using for PTO packets that was flat-out\r\nincorrect (my bad).\r\n\r\nIn addition to that, there are several other tweaks.\r\n\r\n1. Remove SentPacket::cc_in_flight()\r\n\r\n2. Allow in flight bytes to exceed the congestion window.  The only\r\nchange here is to remove a debug assertion; once we started counting PTO\r\npackets properly, this was the only other thing that was standing in the\r\nway of this accounting being better.\r\n\r\n3. Change the way we probe so that we don't probe spaces that don't\r\nrequire a PTO.  Part of the reason we had infinite loops in the past is\r\nthat we were sending a PING in ApplicationData without needing to.  This\r\nis achieved by recording which spaces have an active PTO timer when\r\nprocessing the PTO timer.  We will only send a PING for those spaces.\r\nNote that we will still send outstanding data for a space if there is a\r\nPTO on an earlier space, but only if there is room left for that.\r\n\r\n4. Change the way we acquire the PTO timer and associated values.  We\r\nuse the raw PTO value in some places and the exponentiated value in\r\nother places.  Make separate functions so that this is clearer.  There\r\nare some awkward hacks involved so that everything routes through\r\nthe same functions without invoking the wrath of the borrow checker\r\nhere.\r\n\r\n5. Change the way we stop tracking old lost packets.  The code before\r\nincluded that in the main detect_lost_packets loop, but that was never\r\nnecessary.  This now uses BTreeMap::split_off, which should be a little\r\nfaster.\r\n\r\n6. Track old lost packets for much longer.  This now uses the *current*\r\nPTO timer, which should ensure that they stick around for ages.  The\r\nproblem with dropping lost packets earlier than one PTO is that we were\r\ndropping the number of in-flight packets back to zero in some cases.\r\nThat would result in us no longer probing, even though there could be\r\nunacknowledged ack-eliciting packets.  As the timer was 3x the loss\r\nrecovery timer, this is likely to be larger than one PTO, but if there\r\nare multiple losses or low rttvar, it is possible that we would stop\r\nsending altogether before even one PTO.  (This was compounded by the\r\nfact that we didn't consider probes to be outstanding, so we stopped\r\nretransmissions after a single probe in most cases.)\r\n\r\nOf these, number 5 is separable, but the changes are fairly simple\r\nto review alongside the other changes.\r\n\r\nCloses #835.\r\n\r\nNote: this is built on top of #833.",
